Social living has been reported in a wide range of animal taxa, although explanations for why sociality exists are controversial, largely due to its complexity in nature (

). These living arrangements, also termed social structures, can be described as either solitary (an individual arrangement), paired (two individuals living together, either a dyad or reproductive pair) or group forming (

). While these structures suggest a form of permanency (e.g., monogamous pairings or eusocial groups for joint defence and offspring care) (Duffy, 2002; 

; 

; 

; 

), they can also be formed temporarily (e.g., temporary mate guarding) (

; 

). These arrangements can be described as strict (wherein species typically never deviate from their chosen lifestyle) (Duffy, 2002; 

; 

) or facultative (in which a given species can be seen to have several 
types
of social arrangements) (

, 

; 

; 

). Understanding the nature of social associations is important as they can influence individual fitness, but also because they are often linked to or influence the surrounding ecosystem as many species play vital roles in maintaining their habitats, i.e., ecosystem engineers (

; 

). With this in mind, environmental change can severely impact these interactions, leading to extensive consequences for the wider community. For example, impacts on ecosystem engineers could have effects on the surrounding ecosystem as their role has both direct and indirect effects on community composition (

; 

; 

). Gaining an understanding of animal social structures is therefore vital to ensure all species maintain their roles, and to ensure the continued functioning of the ecosystems they reside in.

Marine invertebrates have the potential to exhibit an array of different social structures and can generate novel insights into current theories of social evolution (

; 

; 

; 

). For example, the snapping shrimp 
Synapheus

regalis
(
Duffy, 1996
)

lives within the canals of sponges (

) and display eusociality, whereby individuals reside in large groups. This results in overlapping generations and a division of labour for defence and offspring care (Duffy, 2002; 

; 

; 

; 

). The group’s reproductive individuals typically consist of 
one queen
and her mate (Duffy, 2002; 

), while the remaining non-breeding group members are allocated to parental care or colony defences (Duffy, 2002; 

; 

). Kinship is thought to be the main factor promoting sociality in species of snapping shrimps, owing to high genetic relatedness between breeders and non-breeders (

; 

; 

). In comparison, many other species of decapods live in pairs with monogamous mating systems (i.e., 
Alpheidae
, 
Hippolytidae
, 
Palaemonidae
, and 
Pinnotheridae
) (

; 

; 

; 

); for example, the burrowing shrimp 

Alpheus bellulus
(
Miya & Miyake, 1969
)

only occurs in monogamous pairs as adults with the pair-bond forming early in their life (

; 

; 

, 

). It is believed that 

A. bellulus

pair bonds form due to the benefits of joint burrow defence and maintenance, and the provision of a readily accessible mate. Finally, certain species of shrimps are solitary, like the ascidian-associated shrimps 

Ascidonia flavomaculata
(
Heller, 1864
)

and 

Ascidonia miserabilis
(
Holthuis, 1951
)

, which live solitarily within a branch of the host ascidian due to competition for resources (i.e., shelter and food) (

; 

). Only temporary mating pairs form, whereby males leave the safety of their shelter in search of females, and males subsequently leave once brooded embryos are established, suggesting a temporary mate guarding system within an overall solitary social structure (

; 

).

While various studies have investigated the social structure of sponge-dwelling shrimps and other crustaceans, burrowing mud shrimps, otherwise known as callianassid shrimp (

Callianassidae 
Dana, 1852

) have been somewhat overlooked. Callianassid shrimps typically have elongated, fragile soft bodies that are protected by calcified plates along the dorsal length of their bodies, as well as possessing three sets of pleopods for swimming and two chelipeds (one of which is enlarged) (

). Their highly cryptic lifestyles make detailed quantification of their social structures much more challenging, as their subterranean burrows allow them to hide and otherwise avoid exposure. As a result, relatively little is known about their social and mating associations (

; 

, 

) compared to their reproductive and population biology (

; 

; 

). Social and mating systems have typically been inferred indirectly, establishing a lack of empirical studies that directly quantify mating and social associations (

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

). An understanding of the causes and consequences of sociality in these callianassid shrimps is essential as they are important ecosystem engineers that affect the surrounding environment and the biota residing in it (

; 

). Behaviour can influence ecological outcomes (i.e., predator-prey, community assembly, human disturbance, ecosystem engineers), and therefore any change in the behaviour or structure of a species can change the ecosystem as a whole. As a result, we must gain a better understanding of their social and reproductive associations to ensure these roles are continued to maintain a functioning ecosystem.

Australia
is home to an endemic burrowing mud shrimp, 

Trypaea australiensis
(
Dana, 1852
)

, with populations that span along the east coast from northern 
Queensland
to southern 
Victoria
(

; 

). Several studies have shown that female and male differences are apparent within a given population of 

T. australiensis

, with males being slightly larger in size compared to females (

; 

; 

, 

). Males are also characterised by an enlarged chela, with the difference in chela size attributed to sex rather than body length (male chela typically larger than that of females) (

; 

; 

; 

). One study of the breeding cycle of 

T. australiensis

confirmed discontinuous (seasonal, production one to five broods) reproduction of a population from the 
New South Wales
(NSW) coast of 
Australia
, with ovigerous females appearing only during the warmer months (

). Like other callianassids, 

T. australiensis

is an important ecosystem engineer, affecting the water quality during their burrow formation and maintenance, this then impacting the surrounding flora and fauna (

; 

; 

; 

). Furthermore, 

T. australiensis

is of great importance to the commercial and recreational fisheries industry, both on a social and economic scale, as a bait source (

; 

). 

showed on average (over one trip), anglers were taking in excess of 200 individuals, while the NSW Department of Primary Industries (DPI) indicated that 

T. australiensis

was moderately fished. DPI then implemented a bag limit for recreational fishermen and a total allowable catch of 
5.1 tonnes
for commercial fisheries, with no discrimination of shrimp sex or size. According to the 2020/2021 stock assessment (

), the fishery for the species is now sustainable. These assessments (which the DPI have acknowledged) have nevertheless potentially underestimated the populations of 

T. australiensis

due to the significant amount of time that has lapsed between survey periods and surveys only being conducted at one location. Without an accurate representation of 

T. australiensis

populations and the effectiveness of these non-discriminate size/ sex catch limits, such lack of understanding regarding species and population ecology has the potential to affect the structure and persistence of their populations. Therefore, research that is focused on understanding the social structure and reproductive behaviour of the species is vital to ensure proper management of populations. This in turn will sustain fisheries and the optimal functioning of the estuarine mud-flat ecosystems.

We hypothesised that 

T. australiensis

has the potential of being found in a given burrow as either a solitary individual, as a pair (of either heterosexual or homosexual composition), or as a group of three or more shrimp, given the diverse array of social structures exhibited by other shrimp species (

; 

; 

). Furthermore, we aimed to investigate the correlates of social association in this species. Specifically, we considered a number of key ecological factors (site and season) and morphological features (body size, sex, and sexual maturity). We finally investigated the sexual composition of any pairs and groups observed to infer the 
type
of mating system exhibited by this species.

Sampling at each of the three sites was conducted two to three hours before low tide in the mid-low intertidal zone. To collect the shrimp, a typical burrow opening was randomly selected and pumped four to six times with a standard nipper pump (
76 cm
in length, 
5 cm
diameter).As these burrows can have multiple openings (a typical burrow as described by 

, a minimum of one-meter distance between burrows and areas where burrows were less densely orientated were selected to avoid the potential of resampling the same burrow. This methodology has been used effectively in several studies (

; 

; 

; 

; 

, 

). Each shrimp from a burrow was collected and assigned individual burrow and shrimp identification numbers. Shrimp were secured on a board, and scaled photographs of the ventral side of each individual were taken for later verification of sex and size (
Fig 1
). Sex was determined by the presence of the second pair of pleopods, which are absent in males and present in females (

). The carapace length and the propodus of the enlarged cheliped length were measured to the nearest 
0.1mm
using plastic callipers and recorded on waterproof paper. The position (left or right) of the major cheliped was also recorded. After measurements were taken, shrimp were then released back to an adjacent area where they were pumped from and monitored until they had safely burrowed again.

When investigating the correlates of social associations, it was found that pairs were more likely to occur during the warmer seasons (i.e., spring and summer) rather than in the winter. Given that 

T. australiensis

typically breeds in warmer months (

), paired shrimp could be occurring for reproductive reasons. Such pairings are likely temporary, given the predominance of solitary shrimp that were obtained. Such transient associations in other callianassid shrimps have been shown in other studies, occurring through the creation of temporary burrow connections by neighbouring shrimp (

; 

), where male shrimp create horizontal burrow connections to neighbouring female burrows (

; 

; 

; 

; 

). Having done so, males then mate with the female before returning to their burrows and closing the burrow connection (

). This behaviour further supports suggestions of temporary pairing for breeding purposes, as opposed to formations of stable monogamous pairs. Similarly, 

study on the Eastern Pacific 

Callichirus seilacheri
(
Bott, 1955
)

found that heterosexual pairings were short-termed that only 7% of the sampled burrows exhibited heterosexual pairs (much less than expected for socially monogamous species). From our study, 

T. australiensis

exhibited adult-only pairs that were more frequently composed of heterosexual pairings when compared to pairs with juveniles and of similar-size individuals, again suggesting temporary pairing for breeding purposes. The observations of 

T. australiensis

are nevertheless preliminary, requiring further investigations of burrow interconnection frequency, mating behaviours, and analyses of parentage to verify the mating system in 

T. australiensis

as well as in other callianassid species.

If

T. australiensis

does form temporary pairs, why not form stable monogamous pairs on a permanent basis, as seen in other crustaceans (i.e., 

; 

; 

)? 
Long-term
monogamy is usually the result of the need for biparental care of young, particularly seen in birds (

; 

; 

). 
The
bi-parental care hypothesis is, however, unlikely to apply to callianassid shrimps as their eggs hatch into free-swimming larvae, after which little parental care is needed (

; 

). 
Alternatively
, it has been suggested that resource limitation and distribution could promote long-term monogamy (

; 

; 

). 
As
callianassid species appear unlimited by mudflat habitat and planktonic food resources, it is also unlikely that callianassids will form permanent pairs due to patchy and limited resources. 
If
one considers burrows as the limiting resource, which is possible due to the energetic costs of burrowing and maintenance (

, 

; RLK, unpublished data), the benefits of joint territory defence and maintenance could select for pair-bonding and long-term monogamy instead. 
It
is noteworthy that some pairs of 

T. australiensis

consisted of 
two females
or 
two males
, although the former was more prevalent. This pairing suggests that other factors, besides reproduction, could explain some instances of pair-formation, whether temporary or permanent in 

T. australiensis


.

Sexual dimorphism could explain the predominance of solitary shrimp in our study, given the average cheliped length for males was found to be statistically larger than for females. As is seen in other callianassid species, individuals with a larger major cheliped (most often males) are typically more likely to protect or infiltrate burrows, and successfully gain access to mates (

; 

; 

). Furthermore, as burrow construction is costly (RLK, unpublished data), the formation of these temporary pairs, and even single-sex pairings, could arise due to the benefits of joint burrow maintenance and construction. The temporary nature of pair forming could be furthered by the maturity composition of the pairings collected, wherein heterosexual pairs were predominant and single-sex pairs were rarely comprised of two sexually mature adults. This sex composition could therefore show a strong competition between adult males, further evident by the lack of burrows shown to be occupied by males together.

While adult-only pairs were more likely to occur as heterosexual or female-female pairs, pairs consisting of an adult and a juvenile exhibited a greater range of sex compositions. Given that adult-juvenile pairs could not be formed for immediate breeding purposes, they could instead be formed to increase the survival of juveniles living under the protection of a larger individual and its burrow. Indeed, burrow cast studies of callianassids have shown that juveniles cohabit with adult shrimp via a smaller burrow branch off the main adult burrow (

; 

; RLK, unpublished data).

In addition, other callianassids typically take 1–1.5 months for larval settlement, and, from settlement, approximately one to two years to reach sexual maturity (
;
). Cohabiting with a larger adult during this time may enable juveniles to safely grow until they reach sexual maturity and become able to defend their own burrow. We also occasionally found groups during sampling, suggesting a facultative social system. Such groups mostly consisted of one male and multiple females, suggesting that groups may form due to reproductive purposes where males compete to monopolise multiple females. Indeed sexual dimorphism in claw size is present in this species, with males typically having larger cheliped length than females, in support of male-male competition over females (
). Furthermore ,
T. australiensis
becomes reproductively mature rather quickly, likely due to their short lifespan (
). Studies on other burrowing shrimp species, such as
Neotrypaea californiensis ( Dana, 1854 )
,
Upogebia pugettensis ( Dana, 1852 )
, and
Callianassa japonica ( Ortmann, 1891 )
, have shown that success rates for viable offspring are much higher in the larger individuals (
;
). From a reproductive standpoint, it would therefore be more advantageous for males to gain access to larger females for copulation (
). If this indeed occurs on the mudflats, it would explain why larger individuals have been found together in groups, as males will likely prefer access to larger females
.

The limitations imposed by sampling within a cryptic environment, as well as shrimp size and the complexity of the burrows of callianassid species (

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

), mean that individuals residing in burrows could simply have not been sampled. This would not only overestimate the proportion of the population apparently associating singly but also underestimate the proportion in social arrangements, i.e., pairs and groups. Additionally, studies have shown that other species of callianassids occurring in pairs (

; 

) occupy different sections within a burrow when individuals are larger in size, while smaller shrimp reside together (

; 

). Meaning that individuals from the same burrow could have been missed during sampling in our study. Juvenile size may have also played a role in sampling bias as sediment turnover from pumps creates low visibility when collecting them. Although each burrow was pumped multiple times, thereby increasing the chances of finding all shrimp present within the burrow, we recognise that some individuals residing within the burrow could simply have escaped sampling.
